Q1. read.csv (base R) vs read_csv (tidyverse) vs fread (data.table)

There are quite a few utilities in R for reading plain text data files. Let us test the speed of reading a moderate sized compressed csv file, admissions.csv.gz, by three programs: read.csv in base R, read_csv in tidyverse, and fread in the popular data.table package.

Which function is fastest? Is there difference in the (default) parsed data types? (Hint: R function system.time measures run times.)

For later questions, we stick to the tidyverse.

I used the code below to calculate an average read time for functions read.csv, read_csv and fread from 3 experiments.

#Tibble to store the read times in:
read_times <- tibble(
  ST_baseR = 1:3, 
  ET_baseR = 0, 
  ST_tidyR = 0,
  ET_tidyR = 0,
  ST_fread = 0,
  ET_fread = 0,
  RT_tidy = 0,
  RT_baseR = 0,
  RT_fread = 0
)

#storing read times into appropriate columns of the tibble from above:
for(i in 1:nrow(read_times)){
  read_times$ST_baseR[i] <- Sys.time()
  admissions_baseR <- read.csv("/mnt/mimiciv/1.0/core/admissions.csv.gz")
  read_times$ET_baseR[i] <- Sys.time()
  read_times$RT_baseR[i] = read_times$ET_baseR[i] - read_times$ST_baseR[i]
  read_times$ST_tidyR[i] <- Sys.time()
  admissions_tidyR <- read_csv("/mnt/mimiciv/1.0/core/admissions.csv.gz")
  read_times$ET_tidyR[i] <- Sys.time()
  read_times$RT_tidy[i] = read_times$ET_tidyR[i] - read_times$ST_tidyR[i]
  read_times$ST_fread[i] <- Sys.time()
  admissions_fread <- read_csv("/mnt/mimiciv/1.0/core/admissions.csv.gz")
  read_times$ET_fread[i] <- Sys.time()
  read_times$RT_fread[i] = read_times$ET_fread[i] - read_times$ST_fread[i]
}

The average read time for `read.csv`, `read_csv` and `fread`, respectively, were 38, 2.4,  and 3. On average, tidyverse `read_csv` was faster than the other methods.     
`read.csv` divides data types to character (including dates) or numeric, turning character variables into factors. Meanwhile, both `read_csv` and `fread` include more detailed information about the data types (i.e. separating dates into POSIX type, which makes working with dates easier) and they include attributes of the data types, such as specifying if numeric values are integers or doubles, etc.

The initial look at admission year variable using a histogram suggested that this variable must be incorrectly formatted. Based on MIMIC IV description, data were collected 2008-2019. Yet, year variable in the tables range from 2110 to 2211. However, additional investigation revealed that this formatting is a de-identification of the year variable to limit the information to a 3-year window which may be revealed later when analyzing the patients data set.

Based on Figure 3E above, there seem to be high number of admissions at hour 0, which would denote midnight. Additionally, there are also large number of admissions at 7am. Using my limited domain knowledge in hospital shift scheduling, I assume these seemingly increased admissions are actually a result of shift change. At 7am new shift begins, thus, admissions staff who start their day at 7am may be entering the data for patients admitted during the previous night if the staff before them got too busy with other tasks.

Based on Figure 4A there seems to be higher number of males admitted overall. Figure 4B further suggests that potentially at all ages there are more males admitted, except after patients are about 70 years old. This is very interesting, since there are well-known effects of estrogen (female hormones) in protecting the women from many cardio-metabolic conditions. Estrogen levels decline significantly after menapause (at about age 60).Additionally, Figure 4C suggests that the females admitted may be overall at higher age compared to males. However, statistical testing would be necessary to evaluate this hypothesis.

Initial plot of test result values (Fig. 6A) revealed an outlier in the Non invasive blood pressure mean values (3.33333^{6} marked with black circle), which is clearly a mistake since it is multiple orders of magnitude higher than the physiological range. Thus, the variable was removed from further analyses. This finding sparked further analysis of result values, and additional outliers were found. A value of 941 for the heart rate variable was also removed since it is not physiological for this variable. Values of 0 for the parameters were not deemed as outliers, considering that patients may have been in severe distress. Figure 6B. represents the final dataset used for analyses.

Q7. Putting things together

Let us create a tibble mimic_icu_cohort for all ICU stays, where rows are

  • first ICU stay of each unique adult (age at admission > 18)

and columns contain at least following variables

  • all variables in icustays.csv.gz
  • all variables in admission.csv.gz
  • all variables in patients.csv.gz
  • first lab measurements during ICU stay
  • first vital measurements during ICU stay
  • an indicator variable thirty_day_mort whether the patient died within 30 days of hospital admission (30 day mortality)
join_keys <- c("subject_id", "stay_id", "first_careunit")
mimic_icu_cohort <- admissions_tble %>% 
  select(-last_careunit, -los, -intime, -outtime) %>% 
  inner_join(y = patients_tble,  by = join_keys) %>%
  select(-last_careunit, -los, -intime, -outtime) %>%
  inner_join(y = labevents_tble, by = join_keys) %>%
  select( -last_careunit, -intime, -outtime) %>%
  rename(lab_test_id = itemid) %>%
  rename(lab_test_name = label) %>%
  rename(lab_test_result = valuenum) %>%
  rename(lab_charttime = charttime) %>%
  inner_join(y = chartevents_tble, by = join_keys) %>%
  rename(vitals_test_id = itemid) %>%
  rename(vitals_test_name = label) %>%
  rename(vitals_test_result = valuenum) %>%
  rename(vitals_charttime = charttime) %>%
  mutate(dod = as.Date(dod)) %>% 
  mutate(outtime = as.POSIXct(outtime)) 

mimic_icu_cohort <- mimic_icu_cohort%>% 
  mutate(thirty_day_mort = if_else(difftime(mimic_icu_cohort$dod, 
    mimic_icu_cohort$intime, units = "days")<=30, T, F)) %>% 
  mutate(thirty_day_mort = if_else(is.na(thirty_day_mort), F, thirty_day_mort))
